Ussing chamber studies A Snapwell insert containing a monolayer of T84 cells was placed in the plexiglass “slider” and inserted into the Ussing chamber (Physiologic Instruments, San Diego, CA, USA) at 37°C and continuously short-circuited by a four electrode, automatic voltage-clamp apparatus which measured short-circuit current (Isc) and transepithelial resistance (TER); chamber fluid resistance was automatically subtracted. Transepithelial resistance was determined by passing 10-s 10-mV current pulses through the tissues. Short-circuit current was measured by passing sufficient current through the tissues via Ag/AgCl electrodes to reduce the spontaneous transepithelial potential to zero. The composition of the tissue bathing solution was (in mM): 140 Na+, 124 Cl−, 21 HCO3-, 5.4 K+, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
